== Setting the Base Difficulty Level

Each skill action includes an entry for Difficulty Level (DL), which determines how easy or difficult it is to execute.

The DL used by a skill action can be based on one of the target's _traits_, the skill action's _DL chart_, or a _static DL_..
=== Traits

Some skill actions use an opponent's trait as the base Difficulty Level. For example, Persuade uses the target's Wits, and Ghost Trace uses the target system's Security trait.

_Traits_ are only found in stat blocks for the opposition, never in player-characters, and they are expressed as Difficulty Levels. For example, Rico the food cart vendor has a Wits of Moderate (10), and the local Food Mart's payment system has a Security of Hard (14).
==== Skill Action Difficulty Level Chart

Sometimes, the GM is responsible for setting the base DL. As the GM, use your common sense, along with the guidance provided in the Difficulty Level chart included in the skill action's description.
=== Static DL

Some skill actions have a static Difficulty Level (DL). Instead of referring to an NPC trait or a DL Chart, it simply states the DL. For example, Size Up Opponent has a DL of Moderate (10).
== Adjusting the Difficulty Level

Before making a roll, adjust the base Difficulty Level of the task by taking relevant qualities, conditions, and enhancements into account.


=== Qualities

Qualities are short, freeform descriptors that are not specifically defined by the game's rules. A quality is an aspect of a person, place, or thing. When the GM calls for a roll each quality relevant to the situation raises or lowers the Difficulty Level.

For example, Rico the food cart vendor has the quality, \[Needs the Money\]. Qualities like this can help inform the GM's roleplaying and decision making.

A quality like \[Needs the Money\] means the character probably prioritizes their income and savings over other aspects of their life. They are likely to be thrifty or even penny-pinching.

Places and things can have qualities too. A night club might have the qualities, \[Loud\], \[Dark\], and \[Packed\], or a wooden door could have the quality, \[Solid Oak\], which speaks to its sturdiness and difficulty to break down.

The same quality can raise one Difficulty Level while lowering another. For example, the quality \[Dark\] makes it harder to scan the room and find your friends, so it would raise the DL by one. On the other hand, if you are trying to hide, the \[Dark\] is a benefit, so it would lower the DL by one.

Qualities are added and removed as appropriate. For example, during the day, when the maintenance crew is working, the night club no longer has the qualities \[Dark\], \[Loud\], or \[Packed\] because the lights are on, there's no music, and only a handful of workers are present.
=== Conditions

Conditions are temporary effects on people codified by these rules. \[Off Guard\], \[Distracted\], and \[Hidden\] are examples of conditions that could affect your character.

The entry for each condition includes its name, its causes, how it affects your character, and how to remove it. As with qualities, conditions can raise or lower Difficulty Levels, but they usually have other effects as well.
== Attitude

Using a \[Social\] skill action on someone with a Hostile Attitude toward you raises the Difficulty Level by one.

Using a \[Social\] skill action on someone with a Friendly Attitude toward you lowers the Difficulty Level by one.
== Enhancements

Weapons and gear often include (or can be modified to support) specific features that raise or lower the DL under specific circumstances.

For example, a weapon with recoil compensation lowers the DL of all attacks made with it. Goggles or cyber eyes with low light vision balance the Difficulty Level of skill actions that would otherwise be made more difficult in low light. These effects, whether from a weapon, piece of gear, or cybernetic modification, are collectively known as enhancements.
