== Outcomes

When you use a skill action, roll a d20 and add the appropriate ability score to get the result. Compare the result to the Difficulty Level (DL) to determine the outcome: _success_, _critical success_, _failure_, or _critical failure_.
=== Success

If the result is equal to or greater than the DL, the character _succeeded_.
=== Critical Success

If you rolled a 20 on the die (without adding your ability score), it's called a _Natural 20_, and it counts as a _critical success_. Another way to get a critical success is if your result (including your ability score) is higher than the DL by 10 or more.
=== Failure

If the result is less than the DL, the character _failed_.
=== Critical Failure

If you rolled a 1 on the die (without adding your ability score), it's called a _Natural 1_, and it counts as a _critical failure_. You can also get a critical failure if your result (including your ability score) is less than the DL by 10 or more.
=== Stress and Choice

Some skill actions prescribe two other kinds of outcomes: stress and choice. _Stress_ means you suffer a complication related to whatever you were doing that could alter things if not handled with care. _Choice_ means you or the GM are given a choice about what comes next.
